{{short description|psychotherapy technique}}
'''Guided self-change''' (GSC) treatment has been accepted by [[American Psychological Association]] Division 12, Society of Clinical Psychology, as an empirically supported treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.div12.org/PsychologicalTreatments/treatments/substance_guided.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-07-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927111053/http://www.div12.org/PsychologicalTreatments/treatments/substance_guided.html |archivedate=2014-09-27 |df= }}
</ref>

== Brief description ==
GSC is a brief, cognitive-behavioral, motivational intervention developed in the early 1980s. It is a form of brief [[cognitive behavioral therapy]]. It was first developed for problem drinkers, but has since then, been researched on several populations (e.g., drug abusers, Spanish-speaking alcohol abuses, adolescents).<ref>{{cite journal | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0005791600000070 | doi=10.1016/S0005-7916(00)00007-0 | volume=31 | title=Does enhanced social support improve outcomes for problem drinkers in guided self-change treatment? | journal=Journal of Behavior Therapy and Experimental Psychiatry | pages=41–54}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Linda_Sobell/publication/233485385_Guided_Self-Change_Model_of_Treatment_for_Substance_Use_Disorders/links/0046353c00eaeaae20000000.pdf|format=PDF|title=Guided Self-Change Model of Treatment for Substance Use Disorders|website=Researchgate.net|accessdate=13 October 2018}}</ref>

