{{more citations needed|date=July 2014}} {{update|date=July 2014}} {{Infobox company |name = PowerBar |logo = |type = [[Subsidiary]] |predecessor = |foundation = 1986 |founder = [[Brian Maxwell]], Jennifer Biddulph |location_city = [[Glendale, California]] |location_country = [[United States]] |locations = |area_served = North America, Europe |key_people = |industry = [[Food processing]] |products = Sports nutrition |services = |revenue = US$175 million (estimated, 2013) |operating_income = |net_income = |assets = |equity = |num_employees = |parent = |owner = [[Post Holdings]] |caption= |divisions = |subsid = |homepage = {{URL|http://www.powerbar.com}} |footnotes = }} [[File:Berkeley-downtown-Bay-bridge-SF-in-back-from-Lab.jpg|thumb|Photo of Bay Area (2005), with PowerBar sign just recognizable, at top of high rise in downtown Berkeley (center left)]]
'''PowerBar, Inc.''' is an [[United States|American]] maker of [[energy bar]]s and other related products including [[sports drink]]s, [[energy gel|gels]], and the ''Pria'' bars targeted at women.
==History== With Mike McCollum, the PowerBar company was founded by [[Brian Maxwell]], a [[Canada|Canadian]] athlete and entrepreneur and Maxwell's girlfriend, Jennifer Biddulph, a nutritionist and distance runner who later became his wife, in their kitchen. They used $55,000 in cash to launch the company in 1986 in [[Berkeley, California]]. This was the first "energy bar" for use during competition by endurance athletes, such as ultra marathoners, and cyclists.<ref name=Biddulph>[https://runningmagazine.ca/raising-the-power-bar-the-brian-maxwell-story/ Raising the Power Bar: The Brian Maxwell story], ''Running Magazine'', Dan Hill, September 21, 2010. Retrieved November 10, 2017.</ref> They eventually acquired a headquarters building in downtown Berkeley.
The company eventually reached $150 million in sales before being purchased by [[Nestlé]] in 2000 for $375 million.<ref name=Biddulph /> In February 2007, PowerBar moved its headquarters from [[Berkeley, California]] to the [[Nestlé]] headquarters in [[Glendale, California]]. With the move came the hiring of an entirely new marketing team.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}
On February 3, 2014, [[Post Foods|Post Holdings]] announced it had reached an agreement to acquire PowerBar, Musashi and related worldwide assets from [[Nestlé]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.drugstorenews.com/article/post-acquires-powerbar-musashi-brands-nestle | title=Post acquires PowerBar, Musashi brands from Nestlé | work=Drug Store News | date=February 3, 2014 | accessdate=February 4, 2014}}</ref>
